Highlights of the Cordillera
2015 Census of Population and Density
Total Population, Density and Land Area
 Among the 18 administrative regions, CAR was the most sparsely populated
region in 2015. With a total land area of 19,818.12 square kilometers, the
region’s population density posted at 87 persons per square kilometer.

PSA-CAR Special Release: Highlights of the Cordillera 2015 Census of Population
Population Density of the Region
 From 2000 to 2010, Cordillera became densely populated by 13 persons
residing in every square kilometer of land. But the region grew in density by
26.1 percent or by 18 persons per square kilometer from 2000 to 2015.
 In 2010, there were 82 persons residing in every square kilometer of land in
CAR. The population density of the region increased by 6.5 percent or
5 persons per square kilometer more from 2010 to 2015.
Figure 1. Population Density by Census Year, CAR: 2000, 2010, and 2015
Population Density of City and Provinces
 Among the region’s provinces, the most densely populated was Benguet, with a
population density of 161 persons per square kilometer, which is about
54 percent higher than the population density of the region. Meanwhile, the
most sparsely populated province is Apayao with 26 persons per square
kilometer.
 In 2015, Baguio City, with a land area of 57.51 square kilometers, revealed a
population density of 6,005 persons per square kilometer. That is more than
69 times higher than the region’s population density of 87 persons per square
kilometer.
 Mt. Province remained to have a population density of 65 persons per square
kilometer. In other provinces including Baguio City, the population density
increased from 2010 to 2015.

Densely Populated Municipalities
 With a total of 76 municipalities in the region, the top three most densely
populated municipalities in 2015 were La Trinidad, Benguet with 1,844 persons
residing in every square kilometer of land; followed by Bangued, Abra with
353 persons per square kilometer; and La Paz, Abra with 300 persons per
square kilometer.

Sparsely Populated Municipalities
 The top three most sparsely populated municipalities in 2015 were Tineg, Abra
with only 7 persons residing in every square kilometer of land; followed by
Calanasan, Apayao with 10 persons per square kilometer; and Tubo, Abra with
12 persons per square kilometer.
Figure 3. Top Three Most Sparsely Populated Municipalities, CAR: 2015
Technical Notes
Total population - refers to the sum of household population and institutional population. Household
population comprises of persons who belong to a household while Institutional population comprises of
persons who are found living in institutional living quarters.
Population density - refers to the sum of people living in a particular amount of space (square
kilometer). It is determined by dividing the population of an area by its land area.
